}
    "As we've seen, moving preprocessing to the GPU can lead to substantial speedups. Also, here an important point to note, in above examples the CIFAR dataset the image size is (32, 32, 2), in real world use-cases the the images can be significantly larger which intermn would cause further performance degradation (on CPU the degradation would be much higher compared to GPUs). \n",
    "\n",
    "The fundamental difference here was :\n",
    "1. GPU due to SIMT/D arhcitecure process image much faster. Almost 30x faster.\n",
    "2. Zero copy approach - the OpenCLIP standard pipeline on HuggingFace ```OpenClipProcessor`` loads image in system memory and applies transformation, then same image is copyed to GPU at the time of inference, whilst in our approach we load image in GPU memory and apply transformation there itself along with inferencing\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "Note: the above code snippet is run with ```torch.cuda.empty_cache()```.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Future Optimizations:\n",
    "In this notebook we saw, the basic advanatge, however when we deploy OpenCLIP kind of models in production, naive approaches does not yield great results\n",
    "- **NVIDIA DALI:** For even more advanced pipeline parallelization.\n",
    "- **TensorRT Deployment:** Compiling the model into a high-performance engine for production use in Triton server."
   ]
  }
 ],
